# RELEASE — zsh-btrfs-snapper

Version:  v2.0
Date:     2026-04-12
Platform: openSUSE Tumbleweed
Shell:    zsh 5.9+
Requires: Oh My Zsh, btrfs-progs, snapper

---

## What's in this release

### v2.0 — Modular architecture + snap wrapper + English translation
- Translated all comments and output messages to English
- `snap-list`, `snap-new`, `snap-rollback` extracted to independent plugins
  — `zsh-snap-list` v3.1, `zsh-snap-new` v2.1, `zsh-snap-rollback` v1.2
  — stubs remain for backward compatibility when plugins are not loaded
- `snap()` — new unified entry point with interactive menu:
  - (1) snap-list — list snapshots
  - (2) snap-new — create a snapshot
  - (3) snap-rollback — rollback to a snapshot
  — colored ANSI box border, delegates to independent plugins

### v1.0 — Initial release
- Deployed and validated on a live openSUSE Tumbleweed system
- Every alias and function tested against real btrfs filesystem and snapper configuration

### Snapshot management (snapper)
- `snap-del <id>` — delete snapshot with usage hint if no argument
- `snap-compare <id1> <id2>` — diff files changed between two snapshots
- `snap-important` / `snap-manual` — filtered views not available in native snapper
- Multi-config aliases: `snap-list-root`, `snap-list-home`, `snap-create-root`, `snap-create-home`

### Filesystem maintenance (btrfs)
- `btrfs-scrub` — starts scrub and immediately shows live status
- `btrfs-balance` — accepts configurable dusage/musage thresholds (default 50%)
- `btrfs-balance-threshold` — conditional balance: only runs if disk usage exceeds defined threshold
- `btrfs-snap-size` — uses btrfs qgroup to report actual space used by snapshots (falls back to du)
- `btrfs-health` — aggregated report: filesystem usage + device error stats + scrub status + snapshot summary

### Design decisions
- `btrfs-defrag` intentionally excluded — defragmentation breaks Copy-on-Write on btrfs and increases disk usage
- All functions use `function name { }` syntax to avoid zsh alias/function conflicts on reload
- `rollback-last` provided without confirmation for expert use — documented as such
